  "text": "Several NMR techniques can indicate regions of disorder within otherwise ordered protein structures. When modeling the 3D structure to fit the NMR data, some regions give multiple solutions to the NMR restraints and so appear as ensembles of possible structures. The standard view is that such regions are ordered, but the data are simply insufficient to identify the particular 3D structure. The alternative possibility is that such regions actually lack particular 3D structures because they are disordered. Such ambiguities can be sorted out by additional NMR relaxation experiments that directly measure the motions of the residues in such regions [CITATION_1] ).",
